<p>In a regular pentagon, the golden ratio is found in the ratio of the len=
gths of a diagonal to a side. All five diagonals together form the <a href=
=3D"https://rechneronline.de/pi/pentagram.php">pentagram</a>. The regular p=
entagon forms the side surfaces of one of the five Platonic solids, the <a =
href=3D"https://rechneronline.de/pi/dodecahedron.php">dodecahedron</a>. Fur=
thermore, this shape can be found in four of the thirteen Archimedean solid=
s, the <a href=3D"https://rechneronline.de/pi/icosidodecahedron.php">icosid=
odecahedron</a>, the <a href=3D"https://rechneronline.de/pi/truncated-icosa=
hedron.php">truncated icosahedron</a>, as well as in the <a href=3D"https:/=
/rechneronline.de/pi/rhombicosidodecahedron.php">rhombenicosidodecahedron</=
a> and the <a href=3D"https://rechneronline.de/pi/snub-dodecahedron.php">sn=
ub dodecahedrons</a>.<br>
The pentagon theorem states that a spatial pentagon with equal sides and an=
gles always lies in one plane. So there is no such structure that spans a t=
hree-dimensional space. This does not apply to all other regular polygons, =
except of course for the triangle, which in its general form is always on o=
ne plane anyway. The pentagon theorem was proven in the second half of the =
20th century.<br>
The regular Pentagon appears frequently in architecture. The most famous ex=
ample is of course the headquarters building of the US Department of Defens=
e near Washington. Modern fortifications were often designed in a pentagona=
l shape.</p>
